\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Eddie sat at his desk, his elbows propped on the icy surface, staring down at the tools before him. The nameplate before him read \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Edward Welton\u8220\'93 as if to remind him who he was\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 and what he was supposed to be capable of. But right now, Eddie didn\u8217\'92t feel like an alchemist. He felt like a fraud.}
\par\plain {Two hours had passed since the test began, despite that, he hadn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t lifted a single tool. His fingers hovered just above the alchemical instruments. Flasks, tongs, and glass vials\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but his hands refused to make a move. Instead, they rubbed at his messy silver hair in frustration, tugging at strands that had already begun to fall in front of his eyes. The task in front of him\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a simple enough request, at least in words: turn lead into gold\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 was anything but simple.}
\par\plain {Eddie had read every codex Catherine had shoved at him. Every scroll, tome, and crumbling parchment detailing such a feat\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s impossibility. The transmutation of base metals into gold was a legend. A metaphor\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 something to be aspired to but never achieved. The very foundation of alchemy was based on the understanding that this was }{\f0\fs24\i1 not possible}{. The laws of nature couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t be bent that far. The balance of the world wouldn\u8217\'92t allow it.}
\par\plain {But here he was, sitting at his desk. Surrounded by seasoned alchemists and magicians who, like him, had seen these truths. Eddie wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t some fool. He knew what the job entailed. He knew }{\f0\fs24\i1 what they were asking}{. He\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d seen what it took to even begin to grasp the basic principles of alchemy. And he was damn sure that turning lead into gold was no more possible than flying by flapping your arms.}
\par\plain {Yet, as Eddie glanced around the room. At the others already bent over their tasks with calm, deliberate focus, he couldn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t help but feel the crushing weight of doubt. Were they pretending? Or was he the one who had missed something?}
\par\plain {A sick knot twisted in his stomach. His gaze flicked back to the lead on his desk, the dull, grey metal sitting there as if mocking him. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Lead into gold,\u8220\'93 he muttered, his voice strained. The thought of trying to make this happen felt like trying to fight a bear with a toothpick. }{\f0\fs24\i1 Impossible.}{ And the more he thought about it, the more absurd it all seemed. He could already hear Emma\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s smug tone as she threw him into this test, watching him flounder. She knew this was a lost cause. She had to.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Fuck,\u8220\'93 Eddie cursed, grinding his teeth. His eyes stung with frustration. }{\f0\fs24\i1 How am I supposed to do this?}{ Catherine never prepared him for this kind of nonsense. She\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d taught him the fundamentals. The transformation of one material to another, the study of the elements, the intricate steps of the alchemical process\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 but }{\f0\fs24\i1 this}{? This wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t alchemy. This was some ridiculous, idealistic dream that didn\u8217\'92t even belong in a classroom.}
\par\plain {The more he thought about it, the angrier he became. He had been dragged into this mess, thinking it was the entrance exam he had prepared for. Instead, he was being asked to do the impossible. }{\f0\fs24\i1 Turn lead into gold.}
\par\plain {The more Eddie wrestled with the task, the clearer it became: this wasn\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t about alchemy. It was about something else\hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 a test of his resolve, a challenge designed to make him confront his limitations. To see how far he\u8217\'92d go when faced with the impossible. And for all his studies and preparation, Eddie wasn\u8217\'92t sure if he was ready to face this kind of challenge. He had always believed in the rational, the attainable. Now? He was standing at the edge of a cliff.}
\par\plain {\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You\u8217\'92re asking me to fight a bear with a toothpick at this point, Somers,\u8220\'93 he muttered bitterly, his hands gripping the edge of the desk. He was at a crossroads, and it was dawning on him that no amount of knowledge could help him now.}
\par\plain {It was all or nothing. }}